Republican strategy to resist Obama's re-election
Republican leaders have justified their policy by the need to combat counterfeiting in elections.
However, the Brennan Center considers the last myth, claiming that cases of election counterfeiting in the United States are more rare than cases of deaths from lightning strikes.
In addition, Republican lawyers only counted 300 cases of election counterfeiting in the United States in ten years.
One thing can be said with certainty: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that complicate the process of registration or voting.
This phenomenon took a new toll after the November 2010 elections, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were passed in just one year in 2011, limiting voting rights in 41 states.
The new election laws require the electorate to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register the electorate on the day of the election and deprive citizens of the right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present an identity card with a photograph.
Indiana became the first state to introduce such a requirement.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the Indian law.
The Republican authorities hastened to spread this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills obliged voters to present photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, i.e. 21 million people who have reached the age required to vote, do not have an identity card with a photo issued by their state government body.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affecting young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than <0x24>35,000, 18% of citizens aged 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Students - voters who are thought to vote for candidates from Democrats are not allowed in several states to use an identity card with a photograph issued by their educational institution.
However, the same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, which mainly vote for Republicans, to use the certificates issued by these clubs to vote.
Until 2004, no state required evidence of the existence of U.S. citizenship to vote.
For the first time, such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than ten states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of Latin Americans.
Two-thirds of Latin American voters are believed to vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 abolishing the registration of voters on the day of voting in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those wishing to register.
This restriction did not go without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 election, the voter registration campaign helped put some 10 million citizens on the lists.
At the same time, the measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17 per cent drop in the number of new voters registered in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted early were African Americans, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the total number of voters in the state.
The same thing happened to the Latin Americans.
With only 11% of voters, they accounted for 24% of citizens who voted prematurely.
Unlike the whites, who made up 76% of the voters, only 46% of those who voted in advance.
Of course, the legislators of the Democrats and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several bills were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most ambiguous laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This allowed to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo ID.
However, the new rules that have come into force will undoubtedly hinder the exercise of the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics of the Democrats condemn the bias of the laws that have been passed, seeing in them an obvious tendency to influence the results of the 2012 election in key states.
The Brennan Center’s 2011 report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electorate to win the presidential election.
Too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
There is only one thing, no doubt: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
