Boson Higgs in detail
Last summer, the report that scientists may have been able to detect the Higgs boson caused real excitement – and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, not much or little.
In addition, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted within the framework of the Standard Model – our best, or at least the “less perfect” description of the nature and behavior of matter – but which has previously not been detected in an experimental way.
But physicists are not entirely sure that it is the Higgs boson.
We know, undoubtedly, that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it strongly resemble the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data is not yet available for complete certainty.
Let’s imagine what this is about the Higgs boson, as the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let’s see what that means.
There is, in this world, one law that is absolutely inevitable, that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
To circumvent this rule there is no possibility, don’t even try too hard, otherwise harm yourself.
But although the physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it turns out that there is also one law of a similar nature in it: the principle of Pauli's exclusion, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space in the same state of time.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good-natured citizens, called fermions, who reasonably obey Pauli’s principle.
In the other, bosons collide, an ugly gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything – at least for this principle, which means that they can be quietly in the same place at the same time.
As reported by the site (by the way, quite unusual) Particle Adventure Laboratory Berkeley, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: the mesons we will not talk about here, and the "particles of force" of the boz, through which the main forces of nature and the cotor spread.
These bosons themselves, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic beings as might be thought.
In fact, if you are able to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or "particle of light", which is the "courier" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "breaks" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, about like a stone thrown into the reservoir.
From this “disruption” comes an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon – and hence one of the bosons of “force carriers”.
A more stable field.
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for that boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, has to be "broken".
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very and very high energies, as if it were a frozen stump, the surface of which could only be heated by a very large stone.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like the one that operates in CERN – the Big Adron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! – is needed to achieve such huge energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, others - not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never be held in the refrigerator itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (such as photons, by the way) do not.
So, what "can bring" all this research, Mrs. Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to verify the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to detect the difference between the results of observations and predictions of SM.
In addition, some of them are passionate about finding such a discrepancy, because the slightest inconsistency can open the door to “new physics” and close some of the Model holes.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oh!).
However, no such differences have yet been found in the CERN.
Consequences
The benefits of these studies for the everyday life of the average person are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there is no one.
See: In the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell’s laboratories could not even guess what revolution their work would be.
They predicted their applications in science, but no more.
In fact, already deceased physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in the Bell Laboratories, where a laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the former were impulse) in 1962, said that the laser was originally considered a harbor rather than a harbor.
Just imagine...
In addition, the application can be found for the toolkit accompanying the study.
For example, the same William Boyle himself, during his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although not at all its original purpose, now serves as an “eye” for all digital cameras in the world and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Grand Adron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
