There’s nothing special compared to the world’s exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on the virtual currency, published in October, was interested in this system.
He describes Bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “competitive with the dollar or the euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as “credits” used to promote a video game, which are earned in the process of the game, or which can be purchased (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But the exchange operations are always controlled and processed by a central body.
In Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously account holders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Any transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses, similar to an e-mail.
Only for each new payment can the user choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically using a dual-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to check that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public account that is sent across the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It goes through a mathematical solution sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
This is the hash phase of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hacking" it all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes can easily verify that it is correct.
The transaction thus turns out to be inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user very quickly (less than ten minutes) would like to pay twice for the same amount of money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, as they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the prize is regularly split in half, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are split to one hundred million, leaving an additional reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in computing capacity.
The life of the network has already survived the rise and fall.
Sites offering Bitcoin services were attacked, and bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
“The defect used does not concern the protocol itself,” says Pierre Nuaz, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes real money payments using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this deficiency.
Major players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept such donations.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weitzman Institute in Israel analyzed the book and found that nearly 80% of bitcoins are out of circulation.
“Gigant Sales” was announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Nuaz, another author of the booklet on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which in this way comes out cheaper.
The owner better controls his personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to provide an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by the phone, Pierre Nuaz clarifies, ensuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“Before Bitcoin is approved, it will take some time, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicted.
In its report, the ECB envisages, by the way, revising the various risks that are considered to be increased today in the event of the success of this system.
