Mohammad Morsi seems to be convinced that Egyptians will vote in favour, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Times.
Especially since the call for an accelerated vote is like an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I leave myself with extraordinary powers" which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted for the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they knocked on the door, feeling unable to convey their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society have done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, the backup participants, were rushed to be added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that in most cases the article was voted unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, entertained the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around... time for prayer, as some members of the committee considered that the hours of the Constituent Assembly were incorrectly set.
The text, which was still in voting yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, article 2 ultimately remained an identical article of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of the Sharia are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the implementation of Islamic law is one of the main demands, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would allow for their more stringent application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
“Liberalism,” the liberals answer, who see only a piar in this.
