Poland and Space.
Last week, at the ministerial meeting of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ECA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began a close cooperation with ECA in 1994 and participated actively in a number of projects of the Agency in the following years.
But Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always met with understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory an idea from his innovative work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esso-Peltry and Andre Luis Hirsch Award for Introduction to Cosmonautics.
Dr. Yan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-famous propagandist of spacecraft, and his contribution was appreciated including the fact that one of the craters on the reverse side of the moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925 in Poland a railroad was built, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remains unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket should have been used to dismantle or brake the truck.
The information about this treachery is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, Polish artillery began to think about rocket shots.
The study was carried out by the Arms Engineering Section in cooperation with the professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzhitsky.
From the remaining materials, it can be seen that the studies have reached the stage of practical trials.
But with the arrival of the German troops the work was interrupted.
In 1937 the idea of a photoelectric fighter missile, proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in the specialized printing press, and the following year the work "Air torpedo missile and aerial bomb" by the author Leliva-Khivoblok.
Both projects were developed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all projects of military use of missile technology were undertaken by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work was completed due to the beginning of the war.
The next scientific work, dedicated to cosmonautics, appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautcyce).
The first mention of society is made in the November issue of 1954 of the journal "Problems", which publishes four volume articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that will be engaged in cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already making turnover, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) has been trying to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and already in the autumn of the POA became its actual member.
And the following year, the first Chairman of the POA Kazimezh Zarankevich (1902-1959) became the Vice-President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile, capable of overcoming the distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
An improved version of the RM-1A was subsequently built, and in the summer of 1959 a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested in the Bled desert.
The rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could exceed 14.5 km, and its task was to observe the high wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor of the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-step, its total length was 510 cm, and its initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed which differed in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space volume of 0.4 l, Meteor-1V - 0.34 l, and Meteor-1C - 0.62 l.
The maximum flight range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute developed a Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a start-up weight of 380 kg was able to lift a payload of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
Later, the Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee on Space Studies) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
