"Germans need to play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stefan Sabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany first made it clear that it was voting against the Palestinians’ request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained from voting.
- Why?
Stefan Sabo: Germany does not support the actions of the Israelis in Gaza.
Now Germany needs to be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don’t think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence – not to be too critical of Israel, he said.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a banning zone for flights.
In the end, NATO made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, that is, it is moving from the policy that, so to speak, was governed by the United States, to the very German foreign policy.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that they are only exploring their role so far, but are on the path to a “more normal” foreign policy.
Such a foreign policy as is carried out by France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy from the German point of view mean?
It is the willingness to take a position in their national interests that is not dependent on the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, i.e. on exports and ties to certain regions such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests differ to a large extent from those of other major states, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
First, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Persian Gulf states.
It must therefore be cautious not to offend the public and the elites in the Arab countries.
In any case, it plays its role.
But I wouldn’t give it too much importance, it’s not a completely one-sided connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relations with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States, understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don’t think it was as dramatic a break as the Libyan issue.
It is possible that Germany will even gain a certain amount of respect in this way.
After all, this signals that she should be taken seriously as a player on the international stage and that her interests should be taken into account.
There are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The U.S., on the other hand, clearly vetoed.
Is there a difference between the United States and many European countries?
As a result of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But given the local political situation, of course, the government cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that substantial differences in opinion are not at all as significant as it always seems.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the status of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a unified, non-controversial European policy, but that is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot act as part of a broader approach and are forced to act instead, relying only on their own vision of the situation.
That’s what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will play a leading role in the development of a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
This theme has always been clumsy.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, wouldn’t it really take on the role?
Or is Germany still being given a leading role?
Germany is not accustomed to this, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis – every time Germany takes on an important role, a wide variety of anti-German sentiments are displayed.
The Germans don’t just deal with it.
Actually, it’s an old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It should take into account the most diverse neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So the U.S. influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, who then remains?
The Germans just have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don’t like it, it’s unpleasant or intensifies your disloyalty to you – that’s life!
Stephen Sabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly explore the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, in which he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
