Mexico’s President Enrique Peña Nieto is at the beginning of his career.
As Mexico’s newly elected President Enrique Peña Nieto is preparing to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to look at the difficulties he will face and the mixed expectations of his country’s people.
The traffic in Mexico is now in a particularly sad state.
The city is overloaded with transport at the best time, and since Monday, steel barriers have been erected, crossing several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was done not to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from entering the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will wear a presidential ribbon and take over the government of the country.
There is a difficult task ahead of him.
Mexico has achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calderón, who is now in power, but the country has fallen into a drug war that has already killed nearly 60,000 people in six years.
“My government is declaring to the Mexican people its willingness to fight violence,” Peña Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama earlier this week in the White House’s Occupational Office.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve this goal.
Prior to such statements, next to the US president, Mr. Peña Nieto’s political career developed as governor of his home state of Mexico.
At his home, in a densely populated and vast state surrounding the country’s capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
Straight-line man
In the idyllic town of Vale de Bravo, for example, it is remembered with warmth.
Residents deserve the revival of tourism, the development of the resort area and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Peña Nieto, which differ greatly from the roads with swamps and wells that were previously in this place.
The tables with its name hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
"We are linking hopes of real and serious change to him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, a state congressman from the Peña Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We expect the real and decisive changes that are so urgently needed by our country, especially in the field of security and economic development.
