Bradley Manning did not complain about ill-treatment, the prosecution said.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning’s statements about poor conditions of detention.
During the hearing, increased attention was paid to Manning’s stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence requires the case to be closed on the grounds that Manning's terms of detention were cruel.
The U.S. military is accused of stealing several thousand secret documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that rank-and-file Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of the many opportunities to file a complaint for ill-treatment, which, he said, had been attributed to him.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Mide, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Feyn stated that the records of Manning's weekly visits by the administration of prisons for the nine months of his detention in Quantico, State of Vittniko.
A cross-examination in the context of the appeal for the termination of Manning's case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment was conducted the next day after Manning stated that while in custody, he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is charged with the hijacking of several thousand secret documents during his service in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks has not confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
During the hearing on Friday, Prosecutor Feyn, along with Manning, reviewed the reports that were filled out after Manning’s administration visits during his stay in Quantico prison, where he was under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, the prison staff asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he is assessing the appeal by the prison administration as "excellent" and the general conditions of the detention as "very professionally organized".
The reports in question do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was asked directly about the terms of his content, Feyn claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concern about these issues and that his visiting representatives of the administration had discussed these issues with him and stated that they would be dealt with, but did not fix it in writing.
“They recorded ‘problems are missing’ (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn’t mean I didn’t raise the issue in the conversation,” Manning said.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about ill-treatment with him in January 2011 during a meeting of the commission, which considered the suicidal intentions he expressed in a written form less than a month ago.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to get rid of the “prevention of trauma” regime and soften the terms of the detention.
Representatives of the military leadership explained that a limited detention regime - at a level lower than a surveillance regime to prevent suicide - was introduced for the protection of the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
“I wanted to let the administration know that I’m okay with them to cancel the trauma prevention regime... so that my standard of living improves, from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning witnessed his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months, before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that his thoughts of suicide appeared in Kuwait, and that one day he lost consciousness because of the intense heat.
He explained that it's psychologically very difficult when you're not being told how your destiny is going and what's going on in the outside world.
"My world has collapsed to the base of Camp Arifjan, to the size of my prison," Manning said on Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in this cage.”
While in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small chamber — at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day — in complete solitude.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only mattresses, blankets, hats, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move because sleep or even just lying down during the day was prohibited by the rules.
According to Manning, while he was asleep, there was a constant light in his eyes that penetrated outside the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned to bed at night, he said he was awakened and forced to turn his back.
Manning's lawyer filed an official objection to Manning's ill-treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Levinworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge asked Manning about the statement he made during his testimony on Thursday, that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his room in Quantico, his wife was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners.
Manning said he had not been able to cover up with a blanket during the check-up.
Responding to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from a guard's order that he should throw a blanket that could be covered in, but admitted that no one directly ordered him to throw it away.
Manning said on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not in danger for himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could use a rubber skull or scalp to hurt himself, but did not do so.
That night, according to Manning's testimony, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from the camera.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he had to endure during his detention, and will significantly shorten the sentence if Manning is found guilty by the military court, which is expected to begin his trial at the beginning of next year.
The defense said it plans to offer Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes, and other charges to challenge as excessive.
The resumption of the hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was detained in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the content of detainees with the strictest possible regime.
Among the allegations made by Manning are the hostility, the illegal promotion of data on the Internet, the transmission of information relating to national defence, and the kidnapping of state property or documents.
If he is convicted in all paragraphs of the indictment, he may be sentenced to life in prison.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican descent.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American descent split between the two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico, I walked through the corridor for arrivals, approached the border control area and freezed on the spot.
The signs pointed to two rows: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the other for Extranjeros (Foreigns).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I have been called a Mexican my whole life.
It’s just a conditional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends from New York consider themselves Italian.
Later, I stopped at the complex design "American of Mexican descent".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, at my grandfather’s home, there was no need for conditional names or complex constructions.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to be able to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than the speakers, and I can’t get rid of the American accent.
That’s why I got my American passport and became a place for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when the re-elected President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were the usual issues for the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trafficking.
President Peña Nieto has been eager to talk about the rise of the Mexican economy, thanks to which Mexicans will now, with the same success, be able to stay in Mexico instead of relocating to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Peña Nieto promised to continue the war on drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a serious and carried out issue of old insults.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of their territory under the rifles.
But the Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only for any U.S. state official to silence at least a word of criticism towards Mexico, in the press and among the elites of Mexican society immediately there are complaints that the Americans are attacking the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montesumma are filled with martial arts.
At the same time, the most difficult are the relationships of Mexico with more than 35 million Americans of Mexican descent living in the United States.
You want to talk about insults?
Enough of them.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities in this country for themselves, and those who don’t have such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, so many people of Mexican descent have only one reason: at some point in their family history, someone - father or grandfather - had no opportunity to realize himself in Mexico.
Most often these were Mexicans of a certain type - sluggish, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we will remember it.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today our life is an embodiment of the American dream, we have studied in good schools and arranged for good jobs, but let’s not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confused and unclear, but we know which country to consider as our own.
The United States of America.
We also know that most representatives of the Mexican elite and the ruling class don’t like us.
We answer them the same.
They see in us a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second class people, as non-real Mexicans.
We don’t speak Spanish well enough, and our ties to Mexico aren’t strong enough.
Our existence alone is explained by our failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We wouldn’t be behind the silk curtain now, finding a satisfying life in the United States, but losing spiritual connections.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain frictions between real Mexicans and Americans of Mexican descent - Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes that she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances Americans of Mexican descent do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
Having the best of the two worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
We are Americans in Mexico.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relationships were already insufficiently confused, some Mexican leaders and intelligence officials want to restore their relationship with the diaspora.
They want Americans of Mexican descent to work as Mexican ambassadors and represent their interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a wonderful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, of course.
Nothing's gonna work out.
Too many insults in the past.
And given the gap between the rich and the poor, the rise of corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country to be so beautiful at all.
Excuse me, but deal with this yourself, Amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Americans of Mexican descent are still offended by the way they were recently in Mexico.
Yeah, yeah.
Maybe we have more in common than I thought.
The Old Battles in the New Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could become a fragile foundation for further peace.
Is there a long-term peace between the Arabs and the Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed pushes to a conclusion about the futility of such hopes.
The usual, meaningless controversy about who started the first sounds; many buildings were turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians were killed, most of whom were civilians, and six Israeli stalkers were killed; the first time during the conflict, the stalkers were killed.
However, despite the hopeless ties between Israelis and Palestinians in their eternal conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be seen in different ways, but the events of the “Arab Spring” have surrounded many established realities in the revolt storm, and Palestinians and Israelis have not managed to stay away from the hurricane that shook the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope to get out of this deadly slump.
The War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give reasons for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, will be implemented, the clashes that took place this week have only strengthened the positions of the force on both sides.
The leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, said they had forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group’s leaders have been destroyed and 1.7 million people blocked in one of the most densely populated and problematic corners of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing in popularity on the West Bank of the Jordan River, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, the leaders of Hamas may well come to the conclusion that time is working on them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new, influential and wealthy friends.
The emerging regional leader Turkey, which once was Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas; her example was followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic countries in the Persian Gulf.
Hamas supporters claim the creation of an Islamist half-month around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, which is ruled by the militant group Hezbollah, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamic rebels are pro-Kosoya, where the power of Bashar al-Assad, and Daesh will be overthrown.
The most significant change in the balance of forces in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most densely populated and important Arab country, in Egypt, where under President Muhammad Mursi the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to Hamas’ support.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, is an organization in many ways similar to Hamas, and its leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic settings, Hamas may become a significant player whose voice will not be able to silence even Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusions.
In the military sense, Hamas was overthrown.
The Israeli anti-missile system Iron Dome justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of Hamas’ missiles.
Israelis can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the United States has remained faithful to its unchanged position; many European countries have also blamed the start of the last round of violence against Hamas.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, especially under Benjamin Netanyahu's government, which largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004, about 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets from the Gaza Strip, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of terrorists-deathers, partly because of a wall that is not a barrier that enters the West Bank of the Ivory Coast.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party – as part of the preparations for the January 22 election – has joined with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What’s the point of giving Palestinians their own state?
If we put all power into their hands in the West Bank, will they not start launching missiles from there toward Israel, as their comrades in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and hard to suppress any attempts to raise your heads.
It is possible that supporters of the “hard” line will win; however, their calculations may be rejected in the Arab Spring.
While Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
Israel’s defensive part of the budget is more than all its Arab neighbors, taken together.
Starting a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economy.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel, to a minimum, must take into account the long-term consequences of its policy.
As democratic changes take place in Arab countries, depriving Palestinians of the right to self-determination is a slow-acting bomb that will sooner or later explode in the occupied territories of Israel, like a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repressions are already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that are being carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement are being paid by the growing dissatisfaction of the international community.
Both sides need an external impulse.
The only solution that remains unfailingly appealed by the sound representatives of both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two States and the surrender of territories by Israel in exchange for security.
There is a hope, not too impressive in the short term, that the ceasefire will allow other countries to more effectively influence the sides of the conflict.
Egypt, which has long been in a position to stop arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, are more than ever in a position to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state, which have been adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and settlements in Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more for the establishment of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming UN vote, which could result in the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
Its role in securing Israel at the negotiating table should also be played by President Obama.
During his first term, he had never presented his own peace settlement plan.
When he returns to the White House, he remains reluctant to join in solving the problem.
This is a catastrophic position.
The United States is vitally interested in the stability of the Middle East.
This is only possible in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the law on unified packaging for cigarettes has entered into force.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and the image of the affected parts of the body are contrasted on the naked green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first in world practice Australian law on the same-type packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing logos and colored designs of different brands with the same box of unicorn-olive color with the ugly pictures of their tobacco products, skin diseases and children's skins.
In addition to the various pictures and inscriptions warning of smoking damage, the only difference between the packages, mandatoryly introduced from this Saturday - the names of the brands, which are printed with the same small font.
These are the world’s toughest conditions for packaging tobacco products.
The Federal Government of Australia states that the aim of the measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving this harmful habit of fashion status.
The study found that people who didn’t start smoking before the age of 26 in 99 cases out of 100 never became smokers.
“Obviously, even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging design,” Health Minister Tanya Pliebersek explains, referring to research, which showed that, for example, the crown in the children’s logo is associated with the idea.
Australia is one of the world's fewest smoking countries, so these changes will not affect the profits of transnational corporations, but the possibility of such measures is already being considered by other countries.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market where cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
“This law will lead to serious consequences, unlike those that were conceived by its initiators,” said Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of fake products from China and Indonesia will supply much more of these goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, new laws are contributing to business growth.
Sandra Ha from a small family company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that the demand for cigarettes and silicone case, covering unpleasant pictures on the packaging, has grown rapidly (almost from scratch) and has been high-priced since Philipi has been homeless since two months ago, American Imbriba Toba companies such as American To.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already delivered about 6,000 products to wholesale companies and is expecting a new batch.
This is a good business for us.
The potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the part of the population to which these measures are directed.
After the adoption of a number of laws in Australia that made illegal television advertising of cigarettes and their support for sporting events, as well as banning sellers from displaying cigarettes in a prominent place, the advertising of tobacco products moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from posting advertisements on the internet, but it cannot restrict foreign websites.
“If you’re trading tobacco products and you’ve only got this little gap left, the idea of promoting your product online will seem extremely appealing to you,” explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of brand reviews written by the face of allegedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is it really the handiwork of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he did not regret his strength and time and made a video, or is that the advertising company behind it?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco says the industry is now more busy adapting to new rules than advertising.
Representatives of the tobacco industry have even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states are making claims within the framework of the World Trade Organization, claiming that the trade has been subjected to these unjust, limiting them.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
